~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
The general consensus among engineers is that modern reactors are very reliable. <br>
<br>
Spaceships presently have ridiculous weight restrictions. <br>
<br>
Even family photographs get weighed before loading. <br>
<br>
With 5 times the payload capacity you can build a far more robust vehicle with better safety features(and tiles).<br>
 <br>
After looking over the list of past deaths and near catastrophes at Nasa I have noticed something. Virtually all problems can be attributed to either the combustibility of chemical fuels or a lack of available energy. <br>
<br>
Apollo 13 had an oxygen tank blowup. No oxydiser would be necessary for fuel onboard an NTR and the air supply could be better protected against leaks.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Ofcourse, if something did go wrong it could be a lot worse. It might mean a radiological cleanup. Still, how many nuclear naval vessels have there been in the last few decades which either went critical and blew up or lost control ? None that I'm aware of. <br>
<br>
We tried chemical for space launching. It could have been done better perhaps, with different vehicles tried, but it could also have been done much worse. I think it's reached close to peak efficiency now. Two generations of research has squeezed just about all the power we can out of this method of breaking chemical bonds. <br>
<br>
Sure we can build bigger bolder designs such as the Dyna-Soar, but as Columbia and Challenger demonstrated, these grand visions can disintegrate in an instant. That will always be the danger with using what are essentially giant fireworks.<br>
<br>
I think nuclear power is a far safer option and promises much greater performance aswell. If an accident were to actually happen during the early ascent then it could be more terrible, but simply launching from an island over the ocean would easily negate that issue. <br>
<br>
A nuclear launcher would mean higher temperatures than regular reactors but the reduced fuel mass and lack of an oxydiser make the potential for an explosion far less than that for chemical boosters. Looking over past deaths and near fatal catastrophes you can see that the two main causes have always been the combustible agents used and a lack of energy. These risks are greatly reduced by nuclear engines. <br>
<br>
On top of that, we would require five times less the number of launches used by chemical means to achieve the same payload in orbit. <br>
<br>
NTR's produce negligible amounts of radiation. <br>
<br>
&quot;Accident at splashdown&quot;, &quot;navigational error&quot;, &quot;malfunctioning thruster&quot;, &quot;oxygen tank exploded&quot;, &quot;capsule caught fire&quot;, &quot;within 10 seconds of running out of fuel&quot;, &quot;exploded 73 seconds after liftoff&quot;.<br>
<br>
Common theme among these reported problems: all a result of limited energy and combustible chemical fuels. None of these accidents are likely to have resulted from nuclear fuels. They are non-combustible. Even the navigational problem would have been less probable with an energy rich vehicle. It would become less crucial to rely on mission control for complex energy saving course alterations. <br>
